# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gtk4
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] In computing, a **desktop environment** (**DE**) is an implementation of the desktop metaphor made of a bundle of programs running on top of a computer operating system that share a common graphical user interface (GUI), sometimes described as a graphical shell.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] The desktop environment was seen mostly on personal computers until the rise of mobile computing.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Desktop GUIs help the user to easily access and edit files, while they usually do not provide access to all of the features found in the underlying operating system.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Instead, the traditional command-line interface (CLI) is still used when full control over the operating system is required.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] A desktop environment typically consists of icons, windows, toolbars, folders, wallpapers and desktop widgets (see Elements of graphical user interfaces and WIMP).
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] A GUI might also provide drag and drop functionality and other features that make the desktop metaphor more complete.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] A desktop environment aims to be an intuitive way for the user to interact with the computer using concepts which are similar to those used when interacting with the physical world, such as buttons and windows.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] While the term *desktop environment* originally described a style of user interfaces following the desktop metaphor, it has also come to describe the programs that realize the metaphor itself.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] This usage has been popularized by projects such as the Common Desktop Environment, KDE, and GNOME.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] On a system that offers a desktop environment, a window manager in conjunction with applications written using a widget toolkit are generally responsible for most of what the user sees.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] The window manager supports the user interactions with the environment, while the toolkit provides developers a software library for applications with a unified look and behavior.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] A windowing system of some sort generally interfaces directly with the underlying operating system and libraries.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] This provides support for graphical hardware, pointing devices, and keyboards.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] The window manager generally runs on top of this windowing system.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] While the windowing system may provide some window management functionality, this functionality is still considered to be part of the window manager, which simply happens to have been provided by the windowing system.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Applications that are created with a particular window manager in mind usually make use of a windowing toolkit, generally provided with the operating system or window manager.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] A windowing toolkit gives applications access to widgets that allow the user to interact graphically with the application in a consistent way.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] The first desktop environment was created by Xerox and was sold with the Xerox Alto in the 1970s.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] The Alto was generally considered by Xerox to be a personal office computer; it failed in the marketplace because of poor marketing and a very high price tag.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] With the Lisa, Apple introduced a desktop environment on an affordable personal computer, which also failed in the market.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] The desktop metaphor was popularized on commercial personal computers by the original Macintosh from Apple in 1984, and was popularized further by Windows from Microsoft since the 1990s.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] As of 2014, the most popular desktop environments are descendants of these earlier environments, including the Windows shell used in Microsoft Windows, and the Aqua environment used in macOS.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Microsoft Windows dominates in marketshare among personal computers with a desktop environment.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Computers using Unix-like operating systems such as macOS, ChromeOS, Linux, BSD or Solaris are much less common; however, as of 2015 there is a growing market for low-cost Linux PCs using the X Window System or Wayland with a broad choice of desktop environments.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Among the more popular of these are Google's Chromebooks and Chromeboxes, Intel's NUC, the Raspberry Pi, etc.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] On tablets and smartphones, the situation is the opposite, with Unix-like operating systems dominating the market, including iOS (BSD-derived), Android, Tizen, Sailfish and Ubuntu (all Linux-derived).
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Microsoft's Windows phone, Windows RT and Windows 10 are used on a much smaller number of tablets and smartphones.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] However, the majority of Unix-like operating systems dominant on handheld devices do not use the X11 desktop environments used by other Unix-like operating systems, relying instead on interfaces based on other technologies.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] On systems running the X Window System (typically Unix-family systems such as Linux, the BSDs, and formal UNIX distributions), desktop environments are much more dynamic and customizable to meet user needs.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] In this context, a desktop environment typically consists of several separate components, including a window manager (such as Mutter or KWin), a file manager (such as Files or Dolphin), a set of graphical themes, together with toolkits (such as GTK+ and Qt) and libraries for managing the desktop.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] All these individual modules can be exchanged and independently configured to suit users, but most desktop environments provide a default configuration that works with minimal user setup.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Some window managers‍—‌such as IceWM, Fluxbox, Openbox, ROX Desktop and Window Maker‍—‌contain relatively sparse desktop environment elements, such as an integrated spatial file manager, while others like evilwm and wmii do not provide such elements.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Not all of the program code that is part of a desktop environment has effects which are directly visible to the user.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] KDE, for example, provides so-called KIO slaves which give the user access to a wide range of virtual devices.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] These I/O slaves are not available outside the KDE environment.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] In 1996 the KDE was announced, followed in 1997 by the announcement of GNOME.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Xfce is a smaller project that was also founded in 1996, and focuses on speed and modularity, just like LXDE which was started in 2006.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] A comparison of X Window System desktop environments demonstrates the differences between environments.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] GNOME and KDE were usually seen as dominant solutions, and these are still often installed by default on Linux systems.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] In the early 2000s, KDE reached maturity.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] The Appeal and ToPaZ projects focused on bringing new advances to the next major releases of both KDE and GNOME respectively.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Although striving for broadly similar goals, GNOME and KDE do differ in their approach to user ergonomics.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] KDE encourages applications to integrate and interoperate, is highly customizable, and contains many complex features, all whilst trying to establish sensible defaults.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] GNOME on the other hand is more prescriptive, and focuses on the finer details of essential tasks and overall simplification.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Accordingly, each one attracts a different user and developer community.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Technically, there are numerous technologies common to all Unix-like desktop environments, most obviously the X Window System.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Accordingly, the freedesktop.org project was established as an informal collaboration zone with the goal being to reduce duplication of effort.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] As GNOME and KDE focus on high-performance computers, users of less powerful or older computers often prefer alternative desktop environments specifically created for low-performance systems.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Most commonly used lightweight desktop environments include LXDE and Xfce; they both use GTK+, which is the same underlying toolkit GNOME uses.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] The MATE desktop environment, a fork of GNOME 2, is comparable to Xfce in its use of RAM and processor cycles, but is often considered more as an alternative to other lightweight desktop environments.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] For a while, GNOME and KDE enjoyed the status of the most popular Linux desktop environments; later, other desktop environments grew in popularity.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] In April 2011, GNOME introduced a new interface concept with its version 3, while a popular Linux distribution Ubuntu introduced its own new desktop environment, Unity.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Some users preferred to keep the traditional interface concept of GNOME 2, resulting in the creation of MATE as a GNOME 2 fork.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] The most common desktop environment on personal computers is Windows Shell in Microsoft Windows.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Microsoft has made significant efforts in making Windows shell visually pleasing.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] As a result, Microsoft has introduced theme support in Windows 98, the various Windows XP visual styles, the Aero brand in Windows Vista, the Microsoft design language (codenamed "Metro") in Windows 8, and the Fluent Design System and Windows Spotlight in Windows 10.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Windows shell can be extended via Shell extensions.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Many mainstream desktop environments for Unix-like operating systems, including KDE, GNOME, Xfce, and LXDE, use the X Window System or Wayland, any of which may be selected by users, and are not tied exclusively to the operating system in use.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] The desktop environment for macOS, which is also a Unix-like system, is Aqua, which uses the Quartz graphics layer, rather than using X or Wayland.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] A number of other desktop environments also exist, including (but not limited to) CDE, EDE, GEM, IRIX Interactive Desktop, Sun's Java Desktop System, Jesktop, Mezzo, Project Looking Glass, ROX Desktop, UDE, Xito, XFast.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Moreover, there exists FVWM-Crystal, which consists of a powerful configuration for the FVWM window manager, a theme and further adds, altogether forming a "construction kit" for building up a desktop environment.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] X window managers that are meant to be usable stand-alone — without another desktop environment — also include elements reminiscent of those found in typical desktop environments, most prominently Enlightenment.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Other examples include OpenBox, Fluxbox, WindowLab, Fvwm, as well as Window Maker and AfterStep, which both feature the NeXTSTEP GUI look and feel.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] The Amiga approach to desktop environment was noteworthy: the original Workbench desktop environment in AmigaOS evolved through time to originate an entire family of descendants and alternative desktop solutions.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Some of those descendants are the Scalos, the Ambient desktop of MorphOS, and the Wanderer desktop of the AROS open source OS.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] WindowLab also contains features reminiscent of the Amiga UI.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Third-party Directory Opus software, which was originally just a navigational file manager program, evolved to become a complete Amiga desktop replacement called Directory Opus Magellan.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] OS/2 (and derivatives such as eComStation and ArcaOS) use the Workplace Shell.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Earlier versions of OS/2 used the Presentation Manager.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] The BumpTop project was an experimental desktop environment.
[src:gtk4/desktop-environment] Its main objective is to replace the 2D paradigm with a "real-world" 3D implementation, where documents can be freely manipulated across a virtual table.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Each user interface created by GTK consists of widgets.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] This is implemented in C using `GObject`, an object-oriented framework for C.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The window widget is the main container.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The user interface is then built by adding buttons, drop-down menus, input fields, and other widgets to the window.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] If you are creating complex user interfaces it is recommended to use GtkBuilder and its GTK-specific markup description language, instead of assembling the interface manually.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The toolkit listens for events such as a click on a button, and passes the event to your application.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] This chapter contains some tutorial information to get you started with GTK programming.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] It assumes that you have GTK, its dependencies and a C compiler installed and ready to use.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] If you need to build GTK itself first, refer to the Compiling the GTK libraries section in this reference.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] To begin our introduction to GTK, we’ll start with a very simple application.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] This program will create an empty 200 × 200 pixel window.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Create a new file with the following content named `example-0.c`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] For more information on how to compile a GTK application, please refer to the Compiling GTK Applications section in this reference.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] All GTK applications will, of course, include `gtk/gtk.h`, which declares functions, types and macros required by GTK applications.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Even if GTK installs multiple header files, only the top-level `gtk/gtk.h` header can be directly included by third-party code.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The compiler will abort with an error if any other GTK header is directly included.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] In a GTK application, the purpose of the `main()` function is to create a `GtkApplication` object and run it.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] In this example a `GtkApplication` pointer named `app` is declared and then initialized using `gtk_application_new()`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] When creating a `GtkApplication`, you need to pick an application identifier (a name) and pass it to `gtk_application_new()` as parameter.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] For this example `org.gtk.example` is used.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] For choosing an identifier for your application, see this guide.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Lastly, `gtk_application_new()` takes `GApplicationFlags` as input for your application, if your application would have special needs.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Next the activate signal is connected to the `activate()` function above the `main()` function.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The `activate` signal will be emitted when your application is launched with `g_application_run()` on the line below.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The `g_application_run()` call also takes as arguments the command line arguments (the `argc` count and the `argv` string array).
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Your application can override the command line handling, e.g. to open files passed on the commandline.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Within `g_application_run()` the activate signal is sent and we then proceed into the `activate()` function of the application.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] This is where we construct our GTK window, so that a window is shown when the application is launched.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The call to `gtk_application_window_new()` will create a new `GtkApplicationWindow` and store a pointer to it in the `window` variable.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The window will have a frame, a title bar, and window controls depending on the platform.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] A window title is set using `gtk_window_set_title()`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] This function takes a `GtkWindow` pointer and a string as input.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] As our `window` pointer is a `GtkWidget` pointer, we need to cast it to `GtkWindow`; instead of casting `window` via a typical C cast like `(GtkWindow*)`, `window` can be cast using the macro `GTK_WINDOW()`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] `GTK_WINDOW()` will check if the pointer is an instance of the `GtkWindow` class, before casting, and emit a warning if the check fails.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] More information about this convention can be found in the GObject documentation.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Finally the window size is set using `gtk_window_set_default_size()` and the window is then shown by GTK via `gtk_window_present()`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] When you close the window, by (for example) pressing the X button, the `g_application_run()` call returns with a number which is saved inside an integer variable named `status`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Afterwards, the `GtkApplication` object is freed from memory with `g_object_unref()`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Finally the status integer is returned and the application exits.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] While the program is running, GTK is receiving *events*.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] These are typically input events caused by the user interacting with your program, but also things like messages from the window manager or other applications.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] GTK processes these and as a result, *signals* may be emitted on your widgets.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Connecting handlers for these signals is how you normally make your program do something in response to user input.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The following example is slightly more complex, and tries to showcase some of the capabilities of GTK.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] In the long tradition of programming languages and libraries, this example is called *Hello, World*.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Create a new file with the following content named `example-1.c`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] As seen above, `example-1.c` builds further upon `example-0.c` by adding a button to our window, with the label “Hello World”.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Two new `GtkWidget` pointers are declared to accomplish this, `button` and `box`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The box variable is created to store a `GtkBox`, which is one of GTK’s ways of controlling the size and layout of widgets.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The `GtkBox` widget is created with `gtk_box_new()`, which takes a `GtkOrientation` enumeration value as parameter.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The buttons which this box will contain can either be laid out horizontally or vertically.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] This does not matter in this particular case, as we are dealing with only one button.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] After initializing box with the newly created `GtkBox`, the code adds the box widget to the window widget using `gtk_window_set_child()`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Next the `button` variable is initialized in similar manner.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] `gtk_button_new_with_label()` is called which returns a `GtkButton` to be stored in `button`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Afterwards `button` is added to our `box`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Using `g_signal_connect()`, the button is connected to a function in our app called `print_hello()`, so that when the button is clicked, GTK will call this function.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] As the `print_hello()` function does not use any data as input, `NULL` is passed to it.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] `print_hello()` calls `g_print()` with the string “Hello World” which will print Hello World in a terminal if the GTK application was started from one.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] After connecting `print_hello()`, another signal is connected to the “clicked” state of the button using `g_signal_connect_swapped()`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] This functions is similar to a `g_signal_connect()`, with the difference lying in how the callback function is treated; `g_signal_connect_swapped()` allows you to specify what the callback function should take as parameter by letting you pass it as data.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] In this case the function being called back is `gtk_window_destroy()` and the `window` pointer is passed to it.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] This has the effect that when the button is clicked, the whole GTK window is destroyed.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] In contrast if a normal `g_signal_connect()` were used to connect the “clicked” signal with `gtk_window_destroy()`, then the function would be called on `button` (which would not go well, since the function expects a `GtkWindow` as argument).
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The rest of the code in `example-1.c` is identical to `example-0.c`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The next section will elaborate further on how to add several `GtkWidget`s to your GTK application.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] When creating an application, you’ll want to put more than one widget inside a window.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] When you do so, it becomes important to control how each widget is positioned and sized.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Create a new file with the following content named `example-2.c`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Many widgets, like buttons, do all their drawing themselves.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] You just tell them the label you want to see, and they figure out what font to use, draw the button outline and focus rectangle, etc.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Sometimes, it is necessary to do some custom drawing.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] In that case, a `GtkDrawingArea` might be the right widget to use.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] It offers a canvas on which you can draw by setting its draw function.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The contents of a widget often need to be partially or fully redrawn, e.g. when another window is moved and uncovers part of the widget, or when the window containing it is resized.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] It is also possible to explicitly cause a widget to be redrawn, by calling `gtk_widget_queue_draw()`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] GTK takes care of most of the details by providing a ready-to-use cairo context to the draw function.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] The following example shows how to use a draw function with `GtkDrawingArea`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] It is a bit more complicated than the previous examples, since it also demonstrates input event handling with event controllers.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Create a new file with the following content named `example-3.c`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] When constructing a more complicated user interface, with dozens or hundreds of widgets, doing all the setup work in C code is cumbersome, and making changes becomes next to impossible.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Thankfully, GTK supports the separation of user interface layout from your business logic, by using UI descriptions in an XML format that can be parsed by the `GtkBuilder` class.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Create a new file with the following content named `example-4.c`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Create a new file with the following content named `builder.ui`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Note that `GtkBuilder` can also be used to construct objects that are not widgets, such as tree models, adjustments, etc.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] That is the reason the method we use here is called `gtk_builder_get_object()` and returns a `GObject` instead of a `GtkWidget`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Normally, you would pass a full path to `gtk_builder_add_from_file()` to make the execution of your program independent of the current directory.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] A common location to install UI descriptions and similar data is `/usr/share/appname`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] It is also possible to embed the UI description in the source code as a string and use `gtk_builder_add_from_string()` to load it.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p01] Using GResource it is possible to combine the best of both worlds: you can keep the UI definition files separate inside your source code repository, and then ship them embedded into your application.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] The desktop file provides important information about the application to the desktop shell, such as its name, icon, D-Bus name, commandline to launch it, etc.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] , where it will be found regardless of the current theme.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] , so that tools like dconf-editor can find it.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Other files, such as GtkBuilder ui files, are best loaded from resources stored in the application binary itself.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] GTK includes application support that is built on top of `GApplication`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] In this tutorial we’ll build a simple application by starting from scratch, adding more and more pieces over time.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Along the way, we’ll learn about `GtkApplication`, templates, resources, application menus, settings, `GtkHeaderBar`, `GtkStack`, `GtkSearchBar`, `GtkListBox`, and more.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] The full, buildable sources for these examples can be found in the `examples` directory of the GTK source distribution, or online in the GTK source code repository.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] You can build each example separately by using make with the `Makefile.example` file.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] For more information, see the `README` included in the examples directory.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] When using `GtkApplication`, the `main()` function can be very simple.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] We just call `g_application_run()` and give it an instance of our application class.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] All the application logic is in the application class, which is a subclass of `GtkApplication`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Our example does not yet have any interesting functionality.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] All it does is open a window when it is activated without arguments, and open the files it is given, if it is started with arguments.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] To handle these two cases, we override the `activate()` vfunc, which gets called when the application is launched without commandline arguments, and the `open()` virtual function, which gets called when the application is launched with commandline arguments.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] To learn more about `GApplication` entry points, consult the GIO documentation.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Another important class that is part of the application support in GTK is `GtkApplicationWindow`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Our subclass does not do anything yet, so we will just get an empty window.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] As part of the initial setup of our application, we also create an icon and a desktop file.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Note that `bindir@` needs to be replaced with the actual path to the binary before this desktop file can be used.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] This does not look very impressive yet, but our application is already presenting itself on the session bus, it has single-instance semantics, and it accepts files as commandline arguments.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] In this step, we use a `GtkBuilder` template to associate a `GtkBuilder` ui file with our application window class.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Our simple ui file gives the window a title, and puts a `GtkStack` widget as the main content.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] To make use of this file in our application, we revisit our `GtkApplicationWindow` subclass, and call `gtk_widget_class_set_template_from_resource()` from the class init function to set the ui file as template for this class.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] We also add a call to `gtk_widget_init_template()` in the instance init function to instantiate the template for each instance of our class.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] You may have noticed that we used the `_from_resource()` variant of the function that sets a template.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Now we need to use GLib’s resource functionality to include the ui file in the binary.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] This file has to be converted into a C source file that will be compiled and linked into the application together with the other source files.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] The gnome module of the Meson build system provides the `gnome.compile_resources()` method for this task.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] In this step, we make our application show the content of all the files that it is given on the commandline.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] To this end, we add a member to the struct of our application window subclass and keep a reference to the `GtkStack` there.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] The first member of the struct should be the parent type from which the class is derived.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Here, `ExampleAppWindow` is derived from `GtkApplicationWindow`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] The `gtk_widget_class_bind_template_child()` function arranges things so that after instantiating the template, the `stack` member of the struct will point to the widget of the same name from the template.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Lastly, we add a `GtkStackSwitcher` to the titlebar area in the UI file, and we tell it to display information about our stack.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] The stack switcher gets all its information it needs to display tabs from the stack that it belongs to.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Here, we are passing the label to show for each file as the last argument to the `gtk_stack_add_titled()` function.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] The menu is shown at the right side of the headerbar.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] It is meant to collect infrequently used actions that affect the whole application.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Just like the window template, we specify our menu in a ui file, and add it as a resource to our binary.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] To make the menu appear, we have to load the ui file and associate the resulting menu model with the menu button that we’ve added to the headerbar.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Since menus work by activating GActions, we also have to add a suitable set of actions to our application.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Our preferences menu item does not do anything yet, but the Quit menu item is fully functional.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Note that it can also be activated by the usual Ctrl-Q shortcut.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] The shortcut was added with `gtk_application_set_accels_for_action()`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] A typical application will have a some preferences that should be remembered from one run to the next.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Even for our simple example application, we may want to change the font that is used for the content.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] We are going to use `GSettings` to store our preferences.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Before we can make use of this schema in our application, we need to compile it into the binary form that GSettings expects.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] GIO provides macros to do this in Autotools-based projects, and the gnome module of the Meson build system provides the `gnome.compile_schemas()` method for this task.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Next, we need to connect our settings to the widgets that they are supposed to control.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] One convenient way to do this is to use `GSettings` bind functionality to bind settings keys to object properties, as we do here for the transition setting.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] The code to connect the font setting is a little more involved, since there is no simple object property that it corresponds to, so we are not going to go into that here.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] At this point, the application will already react if you change one of the settings, e.g. using the `gsettings` command line tool.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Of course, we expect the application to provide a preference dialog for these.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Our preference dialog will be a subclass of `GtkDialog`, and we’ll use the same techniques that we’ve already seen: templates, private structs, settings bindings.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Now we revisit the `preferences_activated()` function in our application class, and make it open a new preference dialog.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] We continue to flesh out the functionality of our application.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] GTK supports this with `GtkSearchEntry` and `GtkSearchBar`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] The search bar is a widget that can slide in from the top to present a search entry.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] We add a toggle button to the header bar, which can be used to slide out the search bar below the header bar.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Implementing the search needs quite a few code changes that we are not going to completely go over here.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] The central piece of the search implementation is a signal handler that listens for text changes in the search entry.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] As another piece of functionality, we are adding a sidebar, which demonstrates `GtkMenuButton`, `GtkRevealer` and `GtkListBox`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] The code to populate the sidebar with buttons for the words found in each file is a little too involved to go into here.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] But we’ll look at the code to add a checkbutton for the new feature to the menu.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] To connect the menuitem to the show-words setting, we use a `GAction` corresponding to the given `GSettings` key.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Widgets and other objects have many useful properties.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Here we show some ways to use them in new and flexible ways, by wrapping them in actions with `GPropertyAction` or by binding them with `GBinding`.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] To set this up, we add two labels to the header bar in our window template, named `lines_label` and `lines`, and bind them to struct members in the private struct, as we’ve seen a couple of times by now.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] To make this menu item do something, we create a property action for the visible property of the `lines` label, and add it to the actions of the window.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] The effect of this is that the visibility of the label gets toggled every time the action is activated.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] Since we want both labels to appear and disappear together, we bind the visible property of the `lines_label` widget to the same property of the `lines` widget.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] We also need a function that counts the lines of the currently active tab, and updates the `lines` label.
[src:gtk4/getting-started-p02] See the full source if you are interested in the details.
[src:gtk4/glib-p01] GLib is a general-purpose, portable utility library, which provides many useful data types, macros, type conversions, string utilities, file utilities, a mainloop abstraction, and so on.
[src:gtk4/glib-p01] A wrapper for the POSIX `access()` function.
[src:gtk4/glib-p01] This function is used to test a pathname for one or several of read, write or execute permissions, or just existence.
[src:gtk4/glib-p01] This function is similar to g_malloc(), allocating (`n_blocks` * `n_block_bytes`) bytes, but care is taken to align the allocated memory to with the given alignment value.
[src:gtk4/glib-p01] Additionally, it will detect possible overflow during multiplication.
[src:gtk4/glib-p01] This function is similar to g_aligned_alloc(), but it will also clear the allocated memory before returning it.
[src:gtk4/glib-p01] Frees the memory allocated by g_aligned_alloc().
[src:gtk4/glib-p01] Frees the memory pointed to by `mem`, assuming it is has the given `size` and `alignment`.
