[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME is developed by the GNOME Project, which is composed of both volunteers and paid contributors, the largest corporate contributor being Red Hat.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] It is an international project that aims to develop frameworks for software development, to program end-user applications based on these frameworks, and to coordinate efforts for the internationalization, localization, and accessibility of that software.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] In 2023 and 2024, GNOME received €1,000,000 from Germany's Sovereign Tech Fund.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Since GNOME 2, productivity has been a key focus for GNOME.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] To meet this end, the GNOME Human Interface Guidelines (HIG) were created.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] All GNOME programs share a coherent style of interfaces but are not limited to the employment of the same GUI widgets.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Rather, the design of the GNOME's interface is guided by concepts described in the HIG, itself relying on insights from cognitive ergonomics.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Following the HIG, developers can create high-quality, consistent, and usable GUI programs, as it addresses everything from interface design to the recommended pixel-based layout of widgets.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] However, critics have complained about GNOME ignoring traditional user interface conventions, and the wasting of screen real estate.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] During the GNOME 2 rewrite, many settings deemed of little value to the majority of users were removed.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME aims to make and keep the desktop environment physically and cognitively ergonomic for people with disabilities.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The GNOME Human Interface Guidelines try to take this into account as far as possible but specific issues are solved by special software.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME addresses computer accessibility issues by using the Accessibility Toolkit (ATK) application programming interface, which allows enhancing user experience by using special input methods and speech synthesis and speech recognition software.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Particular utilities are registered with ATK using Assistive Technology Service Provider Interface (AT-SPI), and become globally used throughout the desktop.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Several assistive technology providers, including Orca screen reader and Dasher input method, were developed specifically for use with GNOME.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The internationalization and localization of GNOME software relies on locale, and supports 197 languages with varying levels of completion, with some not being translated at all.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME Shell is the main graphical shell of GNOME.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] It features a top bar holding (from left to right) an Overview button, a clock and an integrated system status menu.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The application menu displays the name of the application in focus and provides access to functions such as accessing the application's preferences, closing the application, or creating a new application window.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The status menu holds various system status indicators, shortcuts to system settings, and session actions including logging out, switching users, locking the screen, and suspending the computer.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Clicking on the Activities button, moving the mouse to the top-left hot corner or pressing the Super key brings up the Overview.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The Overview gives users an overview of current activities and provides a way to switch between windows and workspaces and to launch applications.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The Dash on the bottom houses shortcuts to favorite applications, currently open windows, and an application picker button to show a list of all installed applications.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] A search bar appears at the top and a workspace list for viewing and switching between workspaces is directly above it.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Notifications appear from the top of the shell.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME Classic also adds the minimize and maximize buttons to window headers.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] There are a large number of GTK-based programs written by various authors.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Since the release of GNOME 3.0, GNOME Project concentrates on developing a set of programs that accounts for the GNOME Core Applications.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The commonalities of the GNOME Core Applications are the adherence to the current GNOME Human Interface Guidelines (HIG) as well as the tight integration with underlying GNOME layers like e.g.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GVfs (GNOME virtual filesystem) and also with one another e.g.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GOA (gnome-online-accounts) settings and GNOME Files with Google Drive and GNOME Photos with Google Photos.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Some programs are simply existing programs with a new name and revamped user interface, while others have been written from scratch.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The GNOME project provides a suite of software development tools to facilitate the creation of GNOME software.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] These tools are designed to streamline the development process for the GNOME ecosystem.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] These tools collectively provide a comprehensive development environment for creating software that aligns with the GNOME desktop and its design principles.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME Circle is a collection of applications which have been built to extend the GNOME platform, utilize GNOME technologies, and follow the GNOME human interface guidelines.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME was started on 15 August 1997 by Miguel de Icaza and Federico Mena as a free software project to develop a desktop environment and applications for it.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] It was founded in part because the K Desktop Environment, which was growing in popularity, relied on the Qt widget toolkit which used a proprietary software license until version 2.0 (June 1999).
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] In place of Qt, GTK (formerly called GIMP Toolkit) was chosen as the base of GNOME.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GTK is licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL), a free software license that allows software linking to it to use a much wider set of licenses, including proprietary software licenses.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME itself is licensed under the LGPL for its libraries and the GNU General Public License (GPL) for its applications.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME was formerly a part of the GNU Project, but that is no longer the case.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] In 2021, GNOME Executive Director Neil McGovern publicly tweeted that GNOME was not a GNU project and that he had been asking GNU to remove GNOME from their list of packages since 2019.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] In 2021, GNOME was removed from the list.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME proceeded to remove mentions of any link to GNU from their code and documentation.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The name "GNOME" was initially an acronym for *GNU Network Object Model Environment*, referring to the original intention of creating a distributed object framework similar to Microsoft's OLE, but the acronym was eventually dropped because it no longer reflected the vision of the GNOME project.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The California startup Eazel developed the Nautilus file manager from 1999 to 2001.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] De Icaza and Nat Friedman founded Helix Code (later Ximian) in 1999 in Massachusetts; this company developed GNOME's infrastructure and applications and was purchased by Novell in 2003.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] During the transition to GNOME 2 and shortly thereafter, there were brief talks about creating a *GNOME Office* suite.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] On 15 September 2003 GNOME-Office 1.0, consisting of AbiWord 2.0, GNOME-DB 1.0, and Gnumeric 1.2.0, was released.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Although some release planning for GNOME Office 1.2 was happening on the gnome-office mailing list, and Gnumeric 1.4 was announced as a part of it, the 1.2 release of the suite itself never materialized.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] As of 4 May 2014, the GNOME wiki only mentions "GNOME/GTK applications that are useful in an office environment".
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 2 was released in June 2002 and was very similar to a conventional desktop interface, featuring a simple desktop in which users could interact with virtual objects such as windows, icons, and files.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 2 started out with Sawfish as its default window manager, but later switched to Metacity in GNOME 2.2.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The handling of windows, applications, and files in GNOME 2 is similar to that of contemporary desktop operating systems.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] However, these features can be moved to almost any position or orientation the user desires, replaced with other functions, or removed altogether.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] As of 2009, GNOME 2 was the default desktop for OpenSolaris.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] In 2008, an increasing discontent among the community and developers about the lack of project direction and technical progress prompted the announcement of GNOME 3.0.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Originally, the plan was to make only incremental changes and avoid disruption for users.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] This changed when efforts led to the creation of the GNOME Shell.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 3 brought many enhancements to core software.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Many GNOME Core Applications also went through redesigns to provide a better user experience.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Mutter replaced Metacity as the default window manager, and Adwaita replaced Clearlooks as the default theme.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The release of GNOME 3 caused considerable controversy in the GNU and Linux communities.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Aiming to provide an easy-to-use and uncluttered user experience has led to some criticized design decisions, like the removal of *minimize* and *maximize* buttons, the simplification of configuration options, and visual cues that could lead to confusion.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Among those critical of the early releases of GNOME 3 is Linus Torvalds, the creator of the Linux kernel.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Torvalds abandoned GNOME for a while after the release of GNOME 3.0, saying, "The developers have apparently decided that it's 'too complicated' to actually do real work on your desktop, and have decided to make it really annoying to do".
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Over time, critical reception has grown more positive.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] In 2013, Torvalds resumed using GNOME, noting that "they have extensions now that are still much too hard to find; but with extensions you can make your desktop look almost as good as it used to look two years ago".
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Debian, a Linux distribution that had historically used GNOME 2, switched to Xfce when GNOME 3 was released, but re-adopted GNOME 3 in time for the release of Debian 8 "Jessie".
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Ubuntu switched from Unity to GNOME 3 with several extensions to resemble Unity, such as a persistent left application panel instead of a hidden dock and re-enabling desktop icons, with Ubuntu 17.10 Artful Aardvark in 2017.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] This release also saw the Ubuntu GNOME edition merge with the mainline release.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] However, Ubuntu Unity was then released, keeping the Unity desktop and continuing to update it.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] It immediately follows version 3, but adopts a new versioning scheme and a schedule of future major releases on a fixed six-month cycle (see Release Cycle).
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] With this quicker release cadence, major releases became somewhat leaner, because full rewrites of major packages were not occurring as often as they were in the jumps between GNOME 1.0, 2.0, and 3.0 versions.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 40 organizes the activities overview in a horizontal fashion, instead of using a vertical design like its predecessors.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The release also brings new touchpad gestures.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 42 was released on 23 March 2022 and introduced the option to screen record and switch light/dark themes using a new GTK API called Libadwaita.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Several default apps were replaced with more modern versions such as Text Editor instead of Gedit and Console instead of Terminal.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 43 (Guadalajara) was released on 21 September 2022 and introduced a new quick settings menu, a GNOME Files update to GTK4, and a new 'Device Security' panel in settings, among many other changes.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME Web was updated, bringing in support for web apps and experimental Firefox and Chrome extension support.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 44 (Kuala Lumpur) was released on 22 March 2023.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Named after Kuala Lumpur in recognition of work done by the GNOME.Asia community, GNOME 44 introduced a new file chooser grid view, updated settings panels, and redesigned accessibility settings.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The new quick settings menu introduced in GNOME 43 was updated, alongside the addition of several new apps and improvements to existing apps.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 45 (Rīga) was released on 20 September 2023.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] It introduced redesigned app styles alongside a new activities button, which replaced both the previous "Activities" label and the app menu with a graphical workspace indicator.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Other updates to the system bar included a new camera usage indicator and a keyboard shortcut to open and close the quick settings menu.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 45 also introduced two new image viewer and camera apps, keyboard backlight controls, and numerous enhancements to existing apps.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 46 (Kathmandu) was released on 20 March 2024 and featured an enhanced files app with global search, support for headless remote login via GDM, and a refreshed settings app, amongst many other app changes.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Other system changes included accessibility improvements and experimental support for variable refresh rates.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 47 (Denver) was released on 18 September 2024 and introduced support for user-selected accent colors in Libadwaita applications, allowing greater interface customization.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] It also brought improvements for low-resolution displays through automatic icon scaling, optimizations in screen recording with GPU hardware encoding, and various enhancements to performance, file navigation, and online accounts.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 48 (Bengaluru) was released on 19 March 2025 and is included in Fedora 42 and Ubuntu 25.04.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] This version introduced notification grouping by application (notification stacking), significant performance improvements such as dynamic triple buffering for smoother animations, and optimizations in CPU and memory usage across key system components.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] It also included improvements in file indexing and graphical stability on systems with dedicated GPUs.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 49 (Brescia) was released in September 2025 and is included in Fedora 43 and Ubuntu 25.10.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] It deprecated X11 support, disabling it by default.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] It also replaced the video player Totem and the document viewer Evince with Showtime and Papers, respectively, and introduced shutting down and restarting the computer when logged out.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 50 (Tokyo) was released on 18 March 2026.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 50 removed X11 support from the source code.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] It introduced new parental control features, accessibility improvements such as global options and reduced animations, and optimizations in core applications such as Files (Nautilus) and Calendar.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] It also added improvements to remote desktop with hardware acceleration, expanded graphics support (including enhancements for NVIDIA and variable refresh rates), and new options in system settings.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] By default, GNOME Flashback contains two panels (one on the top, and one to its opposite on the bottom) spanning the width of the screen.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The top panel usually contains navigation menus labeled "Applications" and "Places" in that order, as the "System" menu from GNOME 2.x has been replaced by a control panel in GNOME 3.x.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] These menus hold links to common applications and areas of the file system, respectively.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] A user menu placed on the opposite side of the screen, which has been available since GNOME 2.14 but has become more prominent in GNOME 3.x, holds access to account and system settings as well as options to log out, switch user, and shut down the computer.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The top panel usually contains a clock/calendar and a notification area, which can double as a sort of dock, as well.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The bottom panel is commonly empty by default (other than a set of buttons to navigate between desktops) due to its use in the navigation between windows (windows minimize to the bottom panel by default).
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Users can populate these panels with other completely customizable menus and buttons, including new menus, search boxes, and icons, with the icons in particular (called *launchers*) performing functions similar to the *quick-launch* feature found in the Microsoft Windows 98–Vista taskbar.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Other applications can also be attached to the panels, and the panels are highly reconfigurable: anything on these panels can be moved, removed, or configured in other ways.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The version of GNOME Panel available in the repository for Ubuntu 12.04 offers a modified version of Fallback Mode with the addition of a custom theme and ports of Ubuntu's own Indicators from their old GNOME 2.x desktop.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Trisquel uses Fallback Mode (Flashback) for its main desktop, because GNOME Shell requires 3D acceleration as it relies on graphics composition, while some free software drivers do not support 3D acceleration, among other reasons like more usability and more stability.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Each of the component software products in the GNOME project has its own version number and release schedule.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] However, individual module maintainers coordinate their efforts to create a full GNOME stable release on an approximately six-month schedule, alongside its underlying libraries such as GTK and GLib.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Some experimental projects are excluded from these releases.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Before GNOME 40, GNOME version numbers followed the scheme *v.xx.yy*.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Here, *v* is a major version, which can include large changes such as ABI breakage; these have no regular schedule and occur in response to requirements for large-scale changes.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] *xx* is a minor version, released on the above schedule of approximately every 6 months, in which the 1- or 2-digit number's parity indicates the type of release: if *xx* is even (e.g.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] 3.20) the release is considered stable, whereas if *xx* is odd, it represents a current development snapshot (e.g.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] 3.21) that will eventually evolve into the next stable release.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] 3.20.6; these are made on a frequency of weeks in order to fix issues, add non-breaking enhancements, etc.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME 40 started a new versioning scheme in which a single number is incremented with each semi-annual release.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The number is followed by a dot and then "alpha", "beta", or "rc" for a development release, or a decimal for a minor stable release (much like the *yy* mentioned previously).
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME releases are made to the main FTP server in the form of source code with configure scripts, which are compiled by operating system vendors and integrated with the rest of their systems before distribution.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Most vendors only use stable and tested versions of GNOME and provide it in the form of easily installed, pre-compiled packages.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The source code of every stable and development version of GNOME is stored in the GNOME git source code repository.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] A number of build scripts (such as JHBuild or formerly GARNOME) are available to help automate the process of compiling the source code.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Since the introduction of Discourse forum in 2019, the discussion moved from mailing lists and in October 2022, the project announced the plan to close all its public mailing lists.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME developers and users gather at an annual GUADEC meeting to discuss the current state and the future direction of GNOME.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME incorporates standards and programs from freedesktop.org to better support interoperability with other desktops.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] GNOME is mainly written in C, XML, C++, C#, HTML, Vala, Python, JavaScript, CSS, and more.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] A number of language bindings are available.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The GLib data structures and utilities library, GObject object and type system and GTK widget toolkit along with the Adwaita design language implemented by libadwaita, comprise the central part of the GNOME development platform.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] The GNOME desktop environment does not consist solely of the graphical control element library GTK and the core applications that make use of it.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] There are quite a few additional software packages that make up the GNOME desktop environment, such as the above.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] Wayland support was introduced in GNOME 3.10 and deemed "for the majority of users […] a usable day to day experience" by 3.20, at which point Wayland became the default user session.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] With GNOME 3.24, Wayland compatibility was extended to Nvidia drivers.
[src:gtk4/gnome-p01] In GNOME 3.30 or later, it was possible to run GNOME without X11 running at startup, using only Wayland.
